1 Lesson 1: Importing excel files into R

1.1 Learning objectives

  1. Import excel files from your computer into R using readxl::read_excel

1.2 Introduction

When conducting research, you might conduct an experiment and record observations or you may send out questionnaires and record the responses the participants gave.

This data may be stored in different formats, as .csv (comma separated values), excel files (.xlsx or .xls), SPSS files (.sav) and STATA files (.dta) and many more. R has functionality to work with many different file formats.

1.2.1 Reading in data into R

The following phrases mean the same thing- Read in data/ Load data/ Import data

Meaning:

When you take a data file that is stored on your local computer and bring it over into R.

This lesson would demonstrate methods used to import excel files stored on your local computer into R using the function read_excel from the r package {readxl}.

Letâs begin by opening a new script in Rstudio with File > New File > R Script

1.2.2 Excel files

To import an excel file from your computer into R, you have to know where the file is located.

For example, you want to read into Rstudio an excel file named excel_data.xlsx which is saved on your desktop.

First, you are going to create a new object in RStudio. So letâs give it any name. eg.excel_data

readxl::read_excel() is one of the functions to read excel files. Inside the parentheses (â¦), type the location of the excel file and the file name.

The double colon means that the function on the right comes from the package on the left, so readxl::read_excel() refers to the function read_excel() in the {readxl} package.

Example

If the excel file was imported correctly, then the object created âexcel_dataâ should appear under the Environment tab.

1.2.3 Importing excel files using the environment tab in RStudio

Here are the steps to follow.

  • Click Environment > Import > From Excel .

  • A new window will pop up. Click on browse to search your computer for the excel file.

  • Select the appropriate excel file to open.

  • In the File/URL box, you can see the location of the excel file.

  • Under Import Options, you can change the name of variable that will store your excel file data.

  • Under Code Preview, you can see the code that was used to import the excel file. Thus, you can type it yourself to read in excel files.

  • Again, if the excel file was imported correctly, then the object created âexcel_dataâ should appear under the Environment tab.

1.3 Check the dimensions of your data

A good check to perform after you have imported data into R is to check the dimensions of the data. The dimensions of a data set refer to how many rows and columns are in the data set.

The function dim() is already built into R and can be used to find out the number of rows and columns the data set contains.

Here is an example to determine the number of rows and columns in the data set âexcel_dataâ we previously uploaded in R.

The result of the code dim(excel_data) is shown below. The first number 10 is the number of rows and the second number is the number of columns. (The [1] is to show that this is the first result R is displaying).

1.3.1 Working with different file extensions

Here are some examples of different types of files and the functions used to read them in or write them out. We will go through some of these functions in detail in the upcoming sections.

Extension File Type Reading Writing
.csv Comma-separated values readr::read_csv() readr::write_csv()
.tsv, .txt Tab-separated values readr::read_tsv() readr::write_tsv()
.xls, .xlsx Excel workbook readxl::read_excel() rio::export()
.sav SPSS files haven::read_sav() haven::write_sav()
.json JSON files jsonlite::read_json() jsonlite::write_json()
.mat, â¦ Multiple types rio::import() rio::export()
